    <h1 class="big-heading">What is Drug Abuse?</h1>

    <p>

        Drug abuse is a chronic condition characterized by the compulsive use of drugs, which alters the structure and
        function of the brain, resulting in a loss of control over drug use and negative consequences. DSM-5 criteria
        are used to diagnose drug abuse, which can be caused by both prescription and non-prescription drugs. Effective
        treatment methods include medication, therapy, and support groups.

        <br><br>

        This major public health concern can lead to impaired driving, violence, and an increased risk of infectious
        disease transmission through shared needles. Education is crucial in preventing drug abuse, and seeking
        professional help for diagnosis and treatment is essential.

        <br><br>

        Drug abuse refers to the harmful or hazardous use of both legal and illegal drugs, which can cause physical,
        psychological, social, and other problems. It affects people of all ages, genders, races, and socio-economic
        backgrounds and can lead to addiction, overdose, and other serious consequences.

    </p>

