    <p>

        Addiction is a chronic, relapsing disorder that involves functional changes to brain circuits involved in
        reward, stress, and self-control. Genetic, environmental, and developmental factors can influence the risk of
        addiction, and withdrawal symptoms may occur when attempts are made to stop drug use.

        <br><br>

        Withdrawal symptoms can be managed with the help of healthcare providers, family, friends, support groups, or
        organized treatment programs. Prevention through education and awareness programs is crucial in addressing drug
        addiction. Professional treatment can provide the tools and support needed to overcome addiction and achieve
        long-term recovery.

        <br><br>

        In conclusion, drug addiction is a complex and challenging condition that requires ongoing treatment and
        support. Early intervention, effective treatment, and a commitment to prevention can help individuals overcome
        drug addiction and achieve a healthy, fulfilling life.

    </p>

